queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Server Vulnerable to HTTP Host Header Attack
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application is vulnerable to a Host header attack. A web server commonly hosts several web applications at the same IP address, referring to each application via its "virtual host". To request a specific web application, a client must specify a value in the "Host" request header, indicating which web appication they would like to access. For example, for a web server hosting both example1.com and example2.com at a single IP address, a client must specify either "example1.com" or "example2.com" in the Host request header to access the application they require. If the Host request header value is not properly validated, an attacker can supply a malicious value to cause the web server to exhibit dangerous behavior. For example, it may: dispatch requests to the incorrect virtual host (often the first one in its internal virtual hosts list); redirect to an attacker-controlled domain; permit web cache poisoning; or allow the attacker to manipulate password reset functionality.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Remember that the Host request header is user-specified and should not be trusted. Ensure that strict whitelisting is used to validate the Host header.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Cookies Without Secure Flag Detected
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application serves cookies to the client without their Secure flag set. Setting the Secure flag on sensitive cookies (such as cookies containing session IDs etc.) ensures that they will not be sent over an unencrypted (i.e. non-HTTPS) connection, protecting the session integrity of the user.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Mark/enable the Secure flag on all cookies that contain sensitive user information such as session IDs.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Cookies Without HttpOnly Flag Detected
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application serves cookies without the HttpOnly flag enabled. If this flag is not enabled on a cookie, an attacker can use client-side JavaScript to read or manipulate its value. Conversely, if this flag is enabled, the cookie is no longer accessible via client-side scripts. All cookies not required by client-side scripts (i.e. JavaScript) should have their HttpOnly flags set.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Mark/enable the HttpOnly flag on all cookies that are not required by client-side scripts.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Server Vulnerable to Lucky13 TLS Exploit(CVE-2013-0169)
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application seems to be vulnerable to the LUCKY13 attack. LUCKY13 is a timing attack that can be used against servers implementing some versions of the TLS protocol (1.1 and 1.2) that support cipher suites that use cipher block chaining (CBC). It has the potential to allow attackers to work out the contents of encrypted communications between the client and server.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Disable support for TLS cipher suites that use cipher block chaining (CBC) mode.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Server Software Version(s) Disclosed
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The server reveals information about itself, for example, the name of the server software running on the system and its version information. This can present a security risk by informing attackers whether or not the system is running old, deprecated or vulnerable software, which can help attackers refine their attack strategies. The server can reveal information about itself in non-standard response headers such as X-Powered-By (which gives the name of the running server software) or X-AspNet-Version which reveals a particular version of ASP.NET as the technology powering the web application and by extension that the web server is very likely to be IIS-based.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: As far as possible, disable all signatures that might reveal information about the server.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Application Firewall Present
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application is hosted behind a web application firewall (WAF), which we were able to detect. This is an informational finding only.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: This is an informational finding only. No action is required.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Shell Detected
queryPentestVulnerability.description: Web shell malware is software deployed by a hacker, usually on a victim web server. It can be used to execute arbitrary system commands, which are commonly sent over HTTP or HTTPS. Web shell attacks pose a serious risk to DoD components. Attackers often create web shells by adding or modifying a file in an existing web application. Web shells provide attackers with persistent access to a compromised network using communication channels disguised to blend in with legitimate traffic and they can be used as a permanent backdoor into the targeted web applications and any connected systems.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Remove the file from the server if there is no business need for the same.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Application Does Not Supply a Referrer Policy
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web server does not return a Referrer-Policy header. A Referrer-Policy header instructs the user's browser on whether or not it should pass on information to websites linked to from the web application about where the request originated. This can be useful, for example, for determining how users arrive on your website and which of your other sites they visit after they leave. The referrer policy should be audited carefully before deploying the web application in order to ensure that excessive information about the user's browsing habits is not leaked to other websites unintentionally, especially over unsecured connections. To disable referrer information completely, the Referrer-Policy header can be set to no-referrer. Alternatively, to enable referrer information only on the same origin, the value can be set to same-origin.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Return the Referrer-Policy HTTP header in application responses, containing an appropriate value.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Application Does Not Supply a Permissions Policy
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application does not return a Permissions-Policy header. The Permissions-Policy header (formerly named Feature-Policy) is a HTTP response header returned by web applications that restrict the functionality of the web application in the browser to help safeguard against malicious behavior introduced by attackers. For example, if the website does not need to access the microphone or camera, the feature policy can disable the microphone/camera APIs entirely so that a successful XSS attack would be unable to exploit them. The Permissions-Policy header is not yet a fully-fledged web standard, though it is widely implemented (particularly on mobile browsers, where control over microphone/camera access is most important).
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Introduce a Permissions-Policy header that restricts the APIs available to client-side code to only those necessary for the web application to function correctly.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Insecure clientaccesspolicy.xml file
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The cross-domain policy file specifies the permissions for web clients (such as Java, Adobe Flash, Adobe Reader, etc.) to access data across different domains. For Silverlight, Microsoft adopted a subset of Adobe's cross-domain.xml and created its cross-domain policy file: clientaccesspolicy.xml. Whenever the web client detects that it must request resources from other domains, it will try to look first for a policy file in the target domain to determine whether cross-domain requests (including headers) and socket-based connections are allowed. The main policy file is located in the root directory of the domain.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Determine which sites will be allowed to make the cross-domain connection. Consider the network topology and any authentication mechanisms that will be affected by the configuration or implementation of cross-domain policies.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Server Software Version(s) Disclosed
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The server reveals information about itself, for example, the name of the server software running on the system and its version information. This can present a security risk by informing attackers whether or not the system is running old, deprecated or vulnerable software, which can help attackers refine their attack strategies. The server can reveal information about itself in non-standard response headers such as X-Powered-By (which gives the name of the running server software) or X-AspNet-Version which reveals a particular version of ASP.NET as the technology powering the web application and by extension that the web server is very likely to be IIS-based.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: As far as possible, disable all signatures that might reveal information about the server.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: No DMARC Policy Supplied in Web Application DNS Records
queryPentestVulnerability.description: No DMARC entries were detected in the DNS records for the web application. Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting, and Conformance (DMARC) is a protocol for email authentication that helps prevent email spoofing, where an attacker sends emails claiming to be from your organization, showing a legitimate email address as the sender. Using DNS TXT entries conforming to the DMARC specification, domain owners can help to protect users from email spoofing by allowing email clients to validate that the email is legitimate. The DMARC protocol also allows the domain owner to specify what email clients should do with email received that appears to be spoofed.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Deploy a DMARC policy in the DNS records for the web application as TXT records.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Content-type incorrectly stated
queryPentestVulnerability.description: If a response specifies an incorrect content type, then browsers may process the response in unexpected ways. If the content type is specified to be a renderable text-based format, then the browser will usually attempt to interpret the response as being in that format, regardless of the actual contents of the response. This behavior might lead to otherwise
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: For every response containing a message body, the application should include a single Content-type header that correctly and unambiguously states the MIME type of the content in the response body. Additionally, the response header ""X-content-type-options: nosniff"" should be returned in all responses to reduce the likelihood that browsers will interpret content in a way that disregards the Content-type header.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: DNS Wildcard Enabled for Domain
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application appears to use a DNS wildcard for subdomains. A wildcard subdomain DNS entry will cause any subdomain to direct to your server's IP address, even if that subdomain is not explicitly configured in the DNS records for the main domain. While not a direct threat to the security of your web application, this means that any domain name ending with yourcompany.com (such as www.google.com.yourcompany.com) would resolve to the IP address of the web application hosted at yourcompany.com. If your web server becomes compromised, a wildcard DNS entry may make it easier for an attacker to host a malicious website at a legitimate company subdomain, potentially also taking advantage of any SSL/TLS certificates installed on your server.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Consider removing the wildcard DNS entry if it is not necessary for the correct functioning of the web application.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Deprecated php version
queryPentestVulnerability.description: According to its version, PHP installation on remote hosts is no longer supported. The lack of support means that vendors will not release new security patches for the product. As a result, it may contain security holes.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: It is recommended to upgrade current version to the latest supported PHP version.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Application Permits MIME Type Sniffing
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application does not return an X-Content-Type-Options header. Certain browsers may attempt to "sniff" the MIME type of pages returned by the server, which can create an exploitable vulnerability if the browser attempts to process a response as the incorrect MIME type, or the response itself has been influenced by an attacker in an attempt to deliberately deceive the MIME type sniffer. Inclusion of the X-Content-Type-Options header with the "nosniff" value instructs the browser to accept Content-Type headers returned by the server as authoritative, and not to attempt MIME type sniffing.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Return the X-Content-Type-Options HTTP header in application responses with the value "nosniff".

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Application Does Not Supply a Content Security Policy
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application does not return a Content-Security-Policy header. Content security policy (CSP) is a web security standard designed to make it much harder for an attacker to exploit cross-site scripting (XSS), clickjacking or related vulnerabilities. CSP allows the web server to specify, through the use of the Content-Security-Policy HTTP response header, that clients should not load CSS, JavaScript or other page assets not specifically flagged for inclusion in the page.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Return the Content-Security-Policy HTTP header in application responses, containing an appropriate policy.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Same-Site Scripting
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application is vulnerable to same-site scripting attacks. This vulnerability arises when the DNS records for a domain contain an entry for localhost with a missing trailing dot (.) causing the record to be interpreted as a subdomain while pointing to 127.0.0.1. For example, if the DNS records for example.com contain an entry for localhost without a trailing dot, localhost.example.com would then resolve to 127.0.0.1. This can introduce a vulnerability similar to cross-site scripting (XSS) or allow the theft of sensitive cookies if the user's local machines become compromised.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Resolve the DNS misconfiguration (i.e. adding the missing trailing dot) that gives rise to the same-site scripting vulnerability.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Directory Listing
queryPentestVulnerability.description: Web servers can be configured to automatically list the contents of directories that do not have an index page present. This can aid an attacker by enabling them to quickly identify the resources at a given path, and proceed directly to analyzing and attacking those resources. It particularly increases the exposure of sensitive files within the directory that are not intended to be accessible to users, such as temporary files and crash dumps.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: There is not usually any good reason to provide directory listings, and disabling them may place additional hurdles in the path of an attacker. This can normally be achieved in two ways: Configure your web server to prevent directory listings for all paths beneath the web root; Place into each directory a default file (such as index.htm) that the web server will display instead of returning a directory listing.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Git repository found
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The Git metadata directory (.git) was found in this folder. An attacker can extract sensitive information by requesting a hidden metadata directory created by the version control tool Git. The metadata catalog is used for development purposes and tracking development changes to a set of source codes before submitting it to the central repository (and vice versa). When the code scrolls from the repository to the active server, it should be completed as an export rather than a local working copy, so this issue occurs.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: It is recommended to delete these files from the production system or restrict access to the .git directory.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Web Application Accessible via IP Address
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The web application is accessible by typing its IP address directly into the browser. This can make it more difficult to properly secure, and can result in unintentional exposure of services not intended for end users. Disabling direct access to the server via its IP address may require setting up server name indication (SNI) for web applications served over HTTPS, or placing the server behind a proxy.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Disable direct access to the web application via the IP address of the server.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Operating System Fingerprinted
queryPentestVulnerability.description: We were able to extract some operating system information from the host using OS fingerprinting. While this process cannot always identify the operating system running on the host with 100% accuracy, it can usually narrow it down to broad OS families (e.g. Windows, Linux) which can be useful to attackers wishing to refine their attack strategy.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: As far as possible, try to minimise the amount of information the machine reveals about its operating system over the network.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Banner Grabbing Possible
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The server discloses the services (and software versions) listening on its ports, allowing "banner grabbing" to be used to ascertain which software is listening on its open network ports. An attacker may be able to use this information to identify security vulnerabilities in the server in order to refine their attack strategy.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: As far as possible, disable all signatures that might reveal information about the server and the software running on it.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Open Network Ports Found on Server
queryPentestVulnerability.description: One or more network ports were found open on the server. An open port is a TCP or UDP port number that is configured to accept packets, allowing other machines to connect. Open ports are necessary to allow other machines to connect to the server, and closing all open ports is therefore impractical. For example, web servers almost always have ports 80 and 443 open to serve webpages to users over HTTP/HTTPS. Vulnerabilities can arise, however, when a port is open unnecessarily without the knowledge of system administrators. Insecure/misconfigured software listening on ports (which may include debugging tools left over from development) can offer attackers a way in to a system.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Close any ports that are open unnecessarily.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Server Software Information Disclosed
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The server reveals identity information about itself, including the name of the server. This information can allow for an attacker to craft specific exploitation techniques for the identified server. This may include launching spraying attacks in an attempt to exploit a multitude of vulnerabilities specific to a piece of software. Some areas that this information may be revealed include within HTTP headers, on error pages, within cookie values and within the application itself.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: It is recommended to minimize the amount of server information that is detectable wherever possible. This might include in server headers such as Server, X-Powered-By, other server specific headers, as well as on error pages or within cookies.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: API Permits MIME Type Sniffing
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The API does not return an X-Content-Type-Options header, which may permit MIME type sniffing. Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions (MIME) is a standard used to identify the type of content that is being sent over the internet, such as text, image, audio, etc. MIME sniffing occurs when certain browsers attempt to identify the content type of a particular asset by analyzing, or “sniffing” the content of a file to identify specific patterns or signatures that match known MIME type. This action poses a security risk, as attackers can abuse this to trick a browser into interpreting files as different MIME types, executing malicious code on a user’s computer. It also has the potential to lead to information leakage, as MIME sniffing can reveal sensitive information about users’ habits or application asset contents. Inclusion of the X-Content-Type-Options header with the "nosniff" value instructs the browser to accept Content-Type headers returned by the server as authoritative, and not to attempt MIME type sniffing.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Implement the X-Content-Type-Options HTTP header in application responses with the value "nosniff".

queryPentestVulnerability.name: CORS Misconfiguration Present
queryPentestVulnerability.description: 'The server appears to have a cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) misconfiguration. Cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) describes the process of enabling access to resources from outside the current origin (usually a domain), by relaxing the default same-origin policy (SOP). For instance, if JavaScript embedded in a page at example1.com/home needs to make an API call to example2.com/api, this access would need to be granted by the Access-Control-Allow-Origin HTTP response header served by the web application at example2.com. While CORS can be useful under the right circumstances (for example, for hosting REST APIs accessible to the public) it can open a web application up to cross-domain attacks. CORS should not be confused with anti-cross-site request forgery (CSRF) measures, which are not directly related.'
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: 'Audit the CORS policy carefully, and ensure that it is not inappropriately permissive.'

queryPentestVulnerability.name: API Does Not Supply a Permissions-Policy Header
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The API does not return a Permissions-Policy header in responses. The Permissions-Policy header (formerly named Feature-Policy) is a HTTP response header returned by web applications that restrict the functionality of the web application in the browser to help safeguard against malicious behavior introduced by attackers. For example, if the website does not need to access the microphone or camera, the permissions policy can disable the microphone/camera APIs entirely so that a successful XSS attack would be unable to exploit them. The Feature-Policy header implementation is now deprecated and no longer supported on all versions of every browser.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Implement a Permissions-Policy header that restricts the APIs and browser features available to client-side code to only those necessary for the web application to function correctly. If using a Feature-Policy, it is recommended to switch to a Permissions-Policy as that is now the widely supported header.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Server Vulnerable to Lucky13 TLS Exploit
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The API may be vulnerable to the LUCKY13 attack, a timing attack that can be used against servers implementing versions 1.1 and 1.2 of the TLS protocol that support cipher suites that use cipher block chaining (CBC). This timing attack has the potential to allow attackers to work out the contents of encrypted communications between the client and server, allowing them to view decrypted sensitive information.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Disable support for TLS cipher suites that use cipher block chaining (CBC) mode, especially focusing on versions 1.1 and 1.2 of the TLS protocol.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: API Does Not Supply a Strict-Transport-Security Header
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The API does not return a HTTP Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) header in the responses. HTTP Strict Transport Security is a web security policy mechanism designed to help safeguard against man-in-the-middle (MITM) attacks affecting protocol security such as protocol downgrade attacks, and cookie hijacking caused by transmission of cookies over unencrypted connections. This is implemented through the use of the Strict-Transport-Security header, which informs the browser that the site should only be accessed using HTTPS and can ensure any future access attempts to the application using HTTP are automatically upgraded to HTTPS. This header should include the max-age value, which indicates the time, in seconds, that the browser should remember a site is only to be accessed through HTTPS. It is also recommended to include the includeSubDomains value, which indicated that the specified rule applies to all the sites subdomains, and the preload value, which instructs the browser to always access the site using HTTPS.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Implement the Strict-Transport-Security header in the application responses, ensure the inclusion of the includeSubDomains and preload values and that the appropriate value is set for max-age.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Server Vulnerable to BEAST Exploit
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The asset is vulnerable to the Browser Exploit Against SSL/TLS (BEAST) exploit. BEAST is a vulnerability that can allow an attacker to decrypt the contents of encrypted traffic through a Man-in-the-Middle attack, potentially allowing for sensitive information to be exposed. The protocols that are vulnerable to BEAST are SSL 2.0 and 3.0, and TLS 1.0. As these protocols are now deprecated, they should be disabled, and TLS 1.2 or 1.3 should be enabled.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: Ensure that SSL 2.0 and 3.0, as well as TLS 1.0 protocols are all disabled, enable TLS 1.2 and 1.3. If it is not possible to disable these protocols, ensure that any block-based ciphers suites in the SSL/TLS configuration are disabled.

queryPentestVulnerability.name: Server Software Version(s) Disclosed
queryPentestVulnerability.description: The server reveals information about itself, including the identity of the server and versioning information. This version information can reveal if the server is running an outdated or vulnerable versions. This also allows for an attacker to craft specific exploitation techniques for the identified server and version. Some areas that this information may be revealed include within HTTP headers, on error pages, within cookie values and within the application itself.
queryPentestVulnerability.recommendation: It is recommended to minimize the amount of server information that is detectable wherever possible. This might include in server headers such as Server, X-Powered-By, and X-AspNet-Version and others, as well as on error pages or within cookies.

queryVulnerability.name: Open Network Ports Found on Server
queryVulnerability.description: One or more network ports were found open on the server. An open port is a TCP or UDP port number that is configured to accept packets, allowing other machines to connect. Open ports are necessary to allow other machines to connect to the server, and closing all open ports is therefore impractical. For example, web servers almost always have ports 80 and 443 open to serve webpages to users over HTTP/HTTPS. Vulnerabilities can arise, however, when a port is open unnecessarily without the knowledge of system administrators. Insecure/misconfigured software listening on ports (which may include debugging tools left over from development) can offer attackers a way in to a system.
queryVulnerability.recommendation: Close any ports that are open unnecessarily.

withoutPOC.findingdesc:
The web application was found to have HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) disabled. HSTS is a web security policy mechanism designed to help safeguard against man-in-the-middle (MITM) attacks affecting protocol security such as protocol downgrade attacks, and cookie hijacking caused by transmission of cookies over unencrypted connections. HSTS restricts compliant client software (such as browsers) from interacting with the web application over non-HTTPS connections.

HSTS can be enabled by adding a response header with the name Strict-Transport-Security and the value max-age=expireTime, where expireTime is the time in seconds that browsers should remember that the site should only be accessed using HTTPS. Including the includeSubDomains flag will propagate this to all subdomains.
withoutPOC.seealso: A screenshot showing the absence of the Strict-Transport-Security HTTP response header in an application response.
withoutPOC.solution: Return an appropriate Strict-Transport-Security HTTP header in application responses.
withoutPOC.scanop: ["Here the host is vulnerable to Headers Strict-Transport-Security vulnerability."]
